  "event_preview": "Talladega Superspeedway is a 2.66-mile (4.28 km) tri-oval in Lincoln, Alabama, opened in 1969 with 33-degree banking in the turns and capable of sustaining two-wide drafting packs at speeds that no other NASCAR venue can approach. The Jack Link's 500 is the tenth race of the 2026 NASCAR Cup Series season.\n\nReddick arrives at Talladega having won five of the opening nine races of the season, becoming the first driver since Dale Earnhardt in 1987 to accomplish that feat. He leads the championship standings and will roll off alongside Kyle Larson on the front row, with Denny Hamlin third and Bubba Wallace fourth — three of the top four starting positions belonging to Toyota. All 36 full-time chartered drivers are in the field alongside five open teams — Jesse Love, Joey Gase, Casey Mears, Chad Finchum and Daniel Dye — with one set to miss the race. Dye makes his NASCAR Cup Series debut in the No. 78 for Live Fast Motorsports, having served a NASCAR-mandated suspension earlier in the season.\n\nThe all-time qualifying lap record at Talladega belongs to Bill Elliott, who turned a lap at 212.809 mph (44.998 seconds) during qualifying for the 1987 Winston 500 — a record that has stood for nearly four decades and, following NASCAR's introduction of restrictor plates in 1988, is considered permanently unbreakable. In the restrictor plate era, the fastest qualifying lap at Talladega belongs to David Gilliland, who posted a 191.712 mph lap in 2006.",
